mreply
=====

Why?
-----

mreply exists because replying to patches from mailing lists is often slow
and annoying, especially when those patches do not land directly in your
inbox.

The current tool is a small wrapper around a simpler workflow: give it a
raw message file, a raw message URL or an mbox, open the generated reply
in your editor and then either keep the saved draft or send it with git
send-email.

Requirements
-----

You need Python 3.

If you want to use --reply, you also need git send-email.

You also need a terminal editor such as vim, nvim, nano, or any editor
exposed through VISUAL or EDITOR.

Behavior
-----

It accepts either a raw RFC 5322 message or an mbox source.

If the source contains multiple messages, it opens one reply draft per
message in sequence.

It opens the generated reply draft in your editor, which defaults to vim
unless VISUAL or EDITOR is set.

It prefers visible text/plain content and skips text/plain attachments
when quoting.

It stores drafts under ~/.mreply/YYYY-MM-DD/.

If you save changes and exit, it keeps the draft and with --reply flag,
invokes git send-email.

Editor handling
-----

It uses VISUAL, then EDITOR then falls back to vim.

It parses editor commands like code --wait correctly.

It applies mail-friendly wrapping settings for vim and nvim.

It applies -r wrapping for nano.

Usage
-----

Saving is the default behavior. If you do not pass --reply, mreply creates
or opens the draft and leaves it on disk after a saved edit.

Draft a reply from a raw message file:

    mreply /path/to/message.eml

Draft replies from an mbox file:

    mreply /path/to/message.mbox

Draft a reply from a URL:

    mreply https://lore.kernel.org/all/20260403-some-random-patch/raw

Open an existing draft:

    mreply --draft ~/.mreply/2026-04-03/Re-example-123456.eml

Send the reply with git send-email after saving:

    mreply --reply https://lore.kernel.org/all/20260403-some-random-patch/raw

Send an existing draft:

    mreply --reply --draft ~/.mreply/2026-04-03/Re-example-123456.eml

Help
-----

Show the command help:

    mreply --help

